Instagram Profile Analysis — Flight Atelier

Final report: overview, time dimensions, and media type performance

Intro

AI Highlights

Results are carried by Images. They pull more engagement per post and contribute the larger share overall.

Videos trail on average. They help when timed right but dilute the baseline if treated like filler.

Engagement is hit-skewed: a few posts do the heavy lifting while the median post is modest.

Interactions are surface-level—likes dominate, comments are rare. Strong first-impression, weak depth.

Time Dimensions

AI Highlights

The second week shown outperforms the first—both cadence and resonance click together there.

October is the stronger month; November softens—likely a mix of creative drift and timing.

Monday is the standout day for efficiency yet is under-used. Mid-week gets more posts without matching returns.

By daypart, Evening is the prime window, Afternoon close behind. Morning wins totals mostly on volume, not quality. Night is a sink.

Media Type

AI Highlights

Images are the efficiency and contribution leader. They shine in Evening, then Afternoon—that’s where they set the tone.

Videos improve sharply when moved to Evening (and hold up in Morning); pushed into Afternoon they sag.

The jump in the second week is largely a Video timing/creative shift—proof that placement matters more than pushing more volume.

Overall Conclusion

Overall — What this says about the account

Performance is powered by Images in prime windows. That pairing defines the baseline.

There’s a timing mismatch: the best day (Monday) and best daypart (Evening) aren’t getting proportionate supply.

Videos aren’t a lost cause—they’re situational. In the right slots they pop; scattered elsewhere they drag.

The profile wins attention fast but doesn’t deepen it. Without stronger conversation triggers, lifts won’t compound.
